04511nam a22008535i 9781501502149DE-B159720180327123002.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||180327s2015    gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97815015021497 a10.1515/97815015021492doi  a(DE-B1597)448844  a(OCoLC)917873529  a(OCoLC)979781200  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP95.54b.B354 2015eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a306.442 212231 aBaker, Will,eauthor.10aCulture and Identity through English as a Lingua Franca :bRethinking Concepts and Goals in Intercultural Communication /cWill Baker. 1aBerlin ;Boston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (295 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDevelopments in English as a Lingua Franca [DELF] ;v800tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tTable of contents -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Intercultural communication and ELF -- tChapter 3. Understanding culture through ELF -- tChapter 4. Culture and identity through English as a lingua franca -- tChapter 5. Re-examining intercultural communicative competence: intercultural awareness -- tChapter 6. ELF and intercultural awareness: implications for English language teaching -- tChapter 7. Putting it into practice: A study of a course in ELF and ICA for language learners in Thailand -- tChapter 8. Conclusion -- tAppendices -- tReferences -- tIndex  aThe use of English as a global lingua franca has given rise to new challenges and approaches in our understanding of language and communication. One area where ELF (English as a lingua franca) studies, both from an empirical and theoretical orientation, have the potential for significant developments is in our understanding of the relationships between language, culture and identity. ELF challenges traditional assumptions concerning the purposed 'inexorable' link between a language and a culture. Due to the multitude of users and contexts of ELF communication the supposed language, culture and identity correlation, often conceived at the national level, appears simplistic and naïve. However, it is equally naïve to assume that ELF is a culturally and identity neutral form of communication. All communication involves participants, purposes, contexts and histories, none of which are 'neutral'. Thus, we need new approaches to understanding the relationship between language, culture and identity which are able to account for the multifarious and dynamic nature of ELF communication.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Mrz 2018) 0aEnglish languagezForeign countries. 0aIdentity (Philosophical concept)xSocial aspects. 0aIntercultural communicationxSocial aspects. 0aLingua francas. 4aCulture. 4aEducation. 4aEnglish as a Lingua Franca. 4aIdentity. 4aIntercultural Communication.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2015z9783110438710oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz978-1-5015-0216-30 cprintz978150151062540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501502149423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501502149.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGGb2015  aZDB-23-DSPb2015